    <h1>Documentation</h1>
    <h2>Get started with the CLI</h2>

    <h2>Visual Studio Code</h2>
    <h3>Install the extension</h3>
    <p>To install the extension, go to the extension tab in Visual Studio Code and search for <b>3D2P</b>.</p>
    GIF

    <h3>Create a 3D2P file</h3>
    <p>Open a folder - ideally it already contains all your project files like images, STLs and a readme.</p>
    <p>Inside your folder press <b>Ctrl+Shift+P</b> to open the command bar in Visual Studio Code. Enter <b>3D2P: Init</b>.</p>
    <p>Press enter and follow the prompts.</p>
    GIF

    <h3>Adding STLs</h3>
    <p>The easiest way to add STLs to your 3D2P file is to open them directly in Visual Studio Code. <b>Right-Click a STL</b>
    and select <b>3D2P: Open STL</b>.</p>
    <p>The STL Viewer should open. From here press <b>addSTLtoProject</b>.</p>
    GIF

    <h3>Adding Notes</h3>
    <p>After adding the STL to your project, your are able to change the Status and Color of the STL directly in the viewer.</p>
    <p>Furthermore you are able to add Notes to your STL by <b>double clicking</b> a position on your model.</p>
    <p>Initially the note is empty and is only a <b>Mark</b>. Press <b>edit</b> and use <b>Markdown</b> to add some information.</p>
    GIF

    <h3>Package the project</h3>
    <p>If you are happy, you are ready to create the 3MF file out of the 3D2P file.</p>
    <p>Press <b>Ctrl+Shift+P</b> again and enter <b>3D2P: Create 3MF</b>. Press enter and wait a bit. The created 3MF file will be
    saved into the root of your opened folder in Visual Studio Code.</p>
    GIF
